article.headline: Tamir scores 18 of 26 points in second half
article.linkText: Cal off to 4-0 start in Pac-10 with win over Huskies
article.story: SEATTLE (AP) -- Amit Tamir was off balance, moving to his left and trying to shake a defender's hand from his face. Swish! It was that kind of night for California's sharp-shooting big man. Tamir scored 18 of his 26 points in the second half as California beat Washington 73-66 Thursday night, giving the Golden Bears a 4-0 conference start for the first time since 1957. "It was a tough win on the road,'' said Tamir, a 6-foot-11 forward from Jerusalem. "We talked about being 4-0. We're feeling pretty comfortable with ourselves right now, and we just have to build on it.'' Tamir shot 6-of-7 from the field in the last 20 minutes, hitting all four of his second-half 3-pointers as California (11-2, 4-0 Pac-10) pulled away from a 29-29 halftime tie to win its fifth straight. It wasn't pretty, though. The scrappy Huskies (6-8, 1-4) made Cal earn this one. Washington had a 40-31 rebounding edge and forced 18 turnovers. Bears coach Ben Braun also expressed concerned that his team shot 22-of-30 from the foul line. Still, California is unbeaten in four league games for the first time since Pete Newell worked the sidelines. "Yeah, I've been told that,'' Braun said. "It's great, but there's a lot of basketball left. I've always talked about maintaining things. You want to finish strong. It's important that we play to a certain level.'' Tamir strained his right knee in a victory over Oregon State last weekend, but it didn't slow him against the Huskies. He hit consecutive 3-pointers to cap a 13-2 run midway through the second half as Cal broke away. "He's got good range,'' Braun said. "He's got good post moves. He's a very, very simple player, a solid all-around player.'' Nate Robinson led Washington with 15 points while Doug Wrenn had 13 points and 10 rebounds, but the Huskies squandered 23 offensive rebounds and lost for the fourth time in five games. "We had great opportunities we didn't take advantage of,'' Washington coach Lorenzo Romar said. "Down the stretch, we lapsed mentally. We outrebounded Cal 40-31 and had 23 offensive rebounds. You would think we would have come out with a victory.'' The Huskies cut the margin to 58-55 when Will Conroy hit a wide-open 3-pointer from the left corner, but Tamir swished his off-balance 3-pointer despite having Wrenn's hand in his face. "I had to laugh on that one,'' Tamir said. "I looked at Doug Wrenn and he looked at me, and we both laughed. It was a lucky shot. After that, they felt like things were going our way.'' That gave Cal a 61-55 lead with 4:02 remaining. "It was difficult to block his shots because he shoots so high,'' Romar said. "He got away from us and got his rhythm.'' The Huskies wouldn't quit, staying as close as 63-60 with two minutes to play. But Joe Shipp made six free throws in the final 32 seconds to preserve the win, Cal's fifth in the last six games against the Huskies. Shipp finished with 19 points, Richard Midgley had 12 and Brian Wethers 11.
